
[1]barm

   B'ARM, n. [L, fermentum, from ferveo; or beer-rahm, beer cream.]

   Yeast; the scum rising upon beer, or other malt liquors, when
   fermenting, and used as leaven in bread to make it swell, causing it to
   be softer, lighter, and more delicate. It may be used in liquors to
   make them ferment or work.
